SIMPLE: stay
RECORDS: 4

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Stay
<hw>Stay</hw> <pr>(st⟦amac⟧)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[AS.
<ets>staeg</ets>, akin to D., G., Icel., Sw., & Dan. <ets>stag</ets>;
cf. OF. <ets>estai</ets>, F. <ets>⟦eacute⟧tai</ets>, of Teutonic
origin.]</ety> <fld>(Naut.)</fld> <def>A large, strong rope, employed to
support a mast, by being extended from the head of one mast down to some
other, or to some part of the vessel. Those which lead forward are
called <xex>fore-and-aft stays</xex>; those which lead to the vessel's
side are called <xex>backstays</xex>. See <xex>Illust.</xex> of
<er>Ship</er>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><mcol><col><b>In stays</b></col>, ⟦or⟧ <col><b>Hove in
stays</b></col></mcol> <fld>(Naut.)</fld>, <cd>in the act or situation
of staying, or going about from one tack to another.</cd> <au>R. H.
Dana, Jr.</au> -- <col><b>Stay holes</b></col> <fld>(Naut.)</fld>,
<cd>openings in the edge of a staysail through which the hanks pass
which join it to the stay.</cd> -- <col><b>Stay tackle</b></col>
<fld>(Naut.)</fld>, <cd>a tackle attached to a stay and used for
hoisting or lowering heavy articles over the side.</cd> -- <col><b>To
miss stays</b></col> <fld>(Naut.)</fld>, <cd>to fail in the attempt to
go about.</cd> <au>Totten.</au> -- <col><b>Triatic stay</b></col>
<fld>(Naut.)</fld>, <cd>a rope secured at the ends to the heads of the
foremast and mainmast with thimbles spliced to its bight into which the
stay tackles hook.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Stay</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Stay
<hw>Stay</hw> <pr>(st⟦amac⟧)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. &
p. p.</pos> <conjf>Stayed</conjf> <pr>(st⟦amac⟧d)</pr> or
<conjf>Staid</conjf> <pr>(st⟦amac⟧d)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Staying</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[OF. <ets>estayer</ets>, F.
<ets>⟦eacute⟧tayer</ets> to prop, fr. OF. <ets>estai</ets>, F.
<ets>⟦eacute⟧tai</ets>, a prop, probably fr. OD. <ets>stade</ets>,
<ets>staeye</ets>, a prop, akin to E. <ets>stead</ets>; or cf.
<ets>stay</ets> a rope to support a mast. Cf. <er>Staid</er>,
<pos>a.</pos>, <er>Stay</er>, <pos>v. i.</pos>]</ety> <sn>1.</sn>
<def>To stop from motion or falling; to prop; to fix firmly; to hold up;
to support.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Aaron and Hur <qex>stayed</qex> up his hands, the one on the one
side, and the other on the other side.</q> <rj><qau>Ex. xvii.
12.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Sallows and reeds . . . for vineyards useful found⟦br⟧
To <qex>stay</qex> thy vines.</q> <rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To support from sinking; to sustain with strength;
to satisfy in part or for the time.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>He has devoured a whole loaf of bread and butter, and it has not
<qex>staid</qex> his stomach for a minute.</q> <rj><qau>Sir W.
Scott.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To bear up under; to endure; to support; to resist
successfully.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>She will not <qex>stay</qex> the siege of loving terms,⟦br⟧
Nor bide the encounter of assailing eyes.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>To hold from proceeding; to withhold; to restrain;
to stop; to hold.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Him backward overthrew and down him <qex>stayed</qex>⟦br⟧
With their rude hands and grisly grapplement.</q>
<rj><qau>Spenser.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>All that may <qex>stay</qex> their minds from thinking that true
which they heartily wish were false.</q> <rj><qau>Hooker.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>To hinder; to delay; to detain; to keep
back.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Your ships are <qex>stayed</qex> at Venice.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>This business <qex>staid</qex> me in London almost a week.</q>
<rj><qau>Evelyn.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>I was willing to <qex>stay</qex> my reader on an argument that
appeared to me new.</q> <rj><qau>Locke.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>6.</sn> <def>To remain for the purpose of; to wait for.</def>
⟦ldquo⟧I <xex>stay</xex> dinner there.⟦rdquo⟧
<rj><au>Shak.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>7.</sn> <def>To cause to cease; to put an end to.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q><qex>Stay</qex> your strife.</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>For flattering planets seemed to say⟦br⟧
This child should ills of ages <qex>stay</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Emerson.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>8.</sn> <fld>(Engin.)</fld> <def>To fasten or secure with stays;
<as>as, to <ex>stay</ex> a flat sheet in a steam boiler</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>9.</sn> <fld>(Naut.)</fld> <def>To tack, as a vessel, so that the
other side of the vessel shall be presented to the wind.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>To stay a mast</b></col> <fld>(Naut.)</fld>, <cd>to
incline it forward or aft, or to one side, by the stays and
backstays.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Stay</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Stay
<hw>Stay</hw> <pr>(st⟦amac⟧)</pr>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <ety>[⟦root⟧163. See
<er>Stay</er> to hold up, prop.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To remain; to
continue in a place; to abide fixed for a space of time; to stop; to
stand still.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>She would command the hasty sun to <qex>stay</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Spenser.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q><qex>Stay</qex>, I command you; <qex>stay</qex> and hear me
first.</q> <rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>I <qex>stay</qex> a little longer, as one <qex>stays</qex>⟦br⟧
To cover up the embers that still burn.</q>
<rj><qau>Longfellow.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To continue in a state.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The flames augment, and <qex>stay</qex>⟦br⟧
At their full height, then languish to decay.</q>
<rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To wait; to attend; to forbear to act.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>I 'll tell thee all my whole device⟦br⟧
When I am in my coach, which <qex>stays</qex> for us.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The father can not <qex>stay</qex> any longer for the fortune.</q>
<rj><qau>Locke.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>To dwell; to tarry; to linger.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>I must <qex>stay</qex> a little on one action.</q>
<rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>To rest; to depend; to rely; to stand; to
insist.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>I <qex>stay</qex> here on my bond.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Ye despise this word, and trust in oppression and perverseness,
and <qex>stay</qex> thereon.</q> <rj><qau>Isa. xxx. 12.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>6.</sn> <def>To come to an end; to cease; <as>as, that day the
storm <ex>stayed</ex></as>.</def> <mark>[Archaic]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Here my commission <qex>stays</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>7.</sn> <def>To hold out in a race or other contest; <as>as, a
horse <ex>stays</ex> well</as>.</def> <mark>[Colloq.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>8.</sn> <fld>(Naut.)</fld> <def>To change tack, as a
ship.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Stay</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 4 ====
HEADWORD: Stay
<hw>Stay</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Cf. OF. <ets>estai</ets>, F.
<ets>⟦eacute⟧tai</ets> support, and E. <ets>stay</ets> a rope to support
a mast.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>That which serves as a prop; a
support.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧My only strength and <xex>stay</xex>.⟦rdquo⟧
<rj><au>Milton.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Trees serve as so many <qex>stays</qex> for their vines.</q>
<rj><qau>Addison.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Lord Liverpool is the single <qex>stay</qex> of this ministry.</q>
<rj><qau>Coleridge.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <pluf>pl.</pluf> <def>A corset stiffened with whalebone
or other material, worn by women, and rarely by men.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>How the strait <qex>stays</qex> the slender waist constrain.</q>
<rj><qau>Gay.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Continuance in a place; abode for a space of time;
sojourn; <as>as, you make a short <ex>stay</ex> in this
city</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Make haste, and leave thy business and thy care;⟦br⟧
No mortal interest can be worth thy <qex>stay</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Embrace the hero and his <qex>stay</qex> implore.</q>
<rj><qau>Waller.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>Cessation of motion or progression; stand;
stop.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Made of sphere metal, never to decay⟦br⟧
Until his revolution was at <qex>stay</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Affairs of state seemed rather to stand at a <qex>stay</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Hayward.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>Hindrance; let; check.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>They were able to read good authors without any <qex>stay</qex>,
if the book were not false.</q> <rj><qau>Robynson (More's
Utopia).</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>6.</sn> <def>Restraint of passion; moderation; caution;
steadiness; sobriety.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark> ⟦ldquo⟧Not grudging that
thy lust hath bounds and <xex>stays</xex>.⟦rdquo⟧
<rj><au>Herbert.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The wisdom, <qex>stay</qex>, and moderation of the king.</q>
<rj><qau>Bacon.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>With prudent <qex>stay</qex> he long deferred⟦br⟧
The rough contention.</q> <rj><qau>Philips.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>7.</sn> <fld>(Engin.)</fld> <def>Strictly, a part in tension to
hold the parts together, or stiffen them.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Stay bolt</b></col> <fld>(Mech.)</fld>, <cd>a bolt or
short rod, connecting opposite plates, so as to prevent them from being
bulged out when acted upon by a pressure which tends to force them
apart, as in the leg of a steam boiler.</cd> -- <col><b>Stay
busk</b></col>, <cd>a stiff piece of wood, steel, or whalebone, for the
front support of a woman's stays. Cf. <er>Busk</er>.</cd> --
<col><b>Stay rod</b></col>, <cd>a rod which acts as a stay, particularly
in a steam boiler.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Stayed</ent>⟦br⟧
